ode is trying to implement a calendar system which can check if an event can be booked or not. The faulty part in the current implementation is that it's allowing overlapping events to be added to the calendar even though they overlap with existing events. 

Here's a fixed version of the `book` function:

```cpp
bool book(int start, int end) {
    auto p = m.upper_bound(start);
    if((p != m.end() && p->first < end) || (p != m.begin() && (--p)->second > start)) 
        return false;

    m[start] = end;
    return true;
}
```
In this fixed version, the event is not booked if there's an existing event in the calendar that overlaps with it. The check for overlap is done by checking whether `p->first < end` (i.e., does the start of the next event fall within the new event?) or `(--p)->second > start` (i.e., does the end of the previous event fall within the new event?). If either condition is true, it means there's an overlap, and the function returns false to indicate that the booking failed.

